<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="[288]">
<HEAD>APPENDIX.<LB>A MORAL ODE.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Egerton MS. 613, fol. 7-12.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ic &aelig;m elder &thorn;&aelig;nne ic w&aelig;s. a winter and a lore</L>
<L>ic w&aelig;lde more &thorn;anne ic dude. mi wit ah to ben more</L>
<L>Wel lange ic habbe child iben. a worde and ec a dede</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;ech ic beo a wintre eald. to &yogh;ung ic eom at rede</L>
<L>Vnnvyt lyf ic habbe &yogh;e-l&aelig;d. and &yogh;uet me &thorn;inh ic lede</L>
<L>&thorn;anne ic me bi-&thorn;anche. wel sore ic me adrede</L>
<L>Mest al &thorn;&aelig;t ic habbe ydon ys idelnesse and chilce</L>
<L N="8">wel late ic habbe me bi &thorn;oht. bute me god do milce</L>
<L>Fele ydele word ic habbe i-que&thorn;en sy&eth;en ic speke cu&thorn;e</L>
<L>and fele &yogh;uinge deden i-do &thorn;at me of-&thorn;inchet nu&thorn;e</L>
<L>Al to lome ic habbe a-gult. a werche and ec a worde</L>
<L N="12">al to muchel ic habbe i-spend. to litel y-leid an horde</L>
<L>Mest al &thorn;at me likede &aelig;r. nu it me mys-liked</L>
<L>&thorn;e muchel fol&yogh;e&thorn; his y-wil. him sulfne he bi-swike&eth;</L>
<L>Ic myhte habbe bet i-don hadde ic &thorn;er y-sel&thorn;e</L>
<L N="16">nu ic wolde, ac ic ne mai. for elde ne for un-hel&thorn;e</L>
<L>Elde me is bi-stolen on. &aelig;r ic hit a-wuste</L>
<L>ne myht ic isen be-fore me. for smeke ne for myste</L>
<L>Ar&yogh;e we beo&thorn; to done god to vuele al to &thorn;riste</L>
<L N="20">more eie stont man of manne. &thorn;anne him det of criste</L>
<L>&THORN;e wel ne de&thorn; &thorn;e hwile he mei wel oft hit hym sc&aelig;l ruwen</L>
<L>&thorn;enne hy mowen sculen and ripen. &thorn;er &thorn;e hi &aelig;r seowen</L>
<L>Don ec to gode wet &yogh;e mu&yogh;e &thorn;a hwile &yogh;e bu&eth; a life</L>
<L N="24">ne hopie no man to muchel to childe ne to wyfe</L>
<L>&THORN;e him selue for-&yogh;ut for wyfe o&thorn;er for childe
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>he s&aelig;l comen on vuele stede. bute hym god be milde</L>
<L>Sende ec sum god be-foren hym. &thorn;e wyle &yogh;e ben aliue</L>
<L N="28">for betere his on almesse before. &thorn;anne ben after vyue</L>
<L>Ne beo &thorn;e leure &thorn;an &thorn;i self &thorn;i mei ne &thorn;i mo&yogh;e</L>
<L>for sot ys &thorn;at ys o&thorn;er mannes frond. betre &thorn;anne his o&yogh;e</L>
<L>Ne hopie wif to hyre were. ne were to his wife</L>
<L N="32">bue for him selue &aelig;frech man. &thorn;e wyle he bo alife</L>
<L>Wis is &thorn;e him sulf be-&thorn;en&thorn; &thorn;a hwile &thorn;e he mot libbe</L>
<L>for sone willet him for-&yogh;yten. &thorn;e fr&aelig;mden and &thorn;o sibbe</L>
<L>&THORN;e wel ne de&thorn; &thorn;e wile he mai. ne scal he wanne he wolde</L>
<L N="36">mani mannes sor &yogh;e-swynch. habbet ofte alle vn-holde</L>
<L>Ne solde no man don a ferst. ne sclakien wel to done</L>
<L>for mani man bi-hoted wel. he it for&yogh;ytet sone</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;e wule siker ben. to habbe godes blisse</L>
<L N="40">do wel him silf &thorn;e wile he mai. &thorn;anne haued he it midywisse</L>
<L>&THORN;os riche men wened ben sikere. &thorn;urh walles and &thorn;urh diche</L>
<L>he ded his eitte on sikere stede. &thorn;e hi send to heuene-riche</L>
<L>For &thorn;er ne &thorn;arf he ben of-drad. of fure ne of &thorn;eve</L>
<L N="44">&thorn;er ne mai it hym bi-nimen. &thorn;e lo&thorn;e ne &thorn;e leue</L>
<L>&THORN;er ne &thorn;erf he habbe kare. of wiue ne of childe</L>
<L>&thorn;ider we sended suuel and bred. to lutel and to selde</L>
<L>&THORN;ider we solden drawen and don. wel oft and wel &yogh;e-lome</L>
<L N="48">for &thorn;er ne scal me us nout bi-nimen. mid wronge ne mid wo&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ider we scolde &yogh;erne drawen and don. wolde &yogh;e me ileue</L>
<L>for &thorn;er ne mai hit ou bi-nimen. &thorn;e king ne &thorn;e scirreve</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at beste &thorn;at we habbet. &thorn;ider we scolde sende</L>
<L N="52">for &thorn;er we it muwen finden eft. and habben abuten ende</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;e her det ani god. for to habben godes ore</L>
<L>al he it scal finden &thorn;er. and hundred felde more</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;e ehte wile healden wel. &thorn;e wile he mai his welden</L>
<L N="56">&yogh;iue his for godes luue. eft heo hit scullen a-finden</L>
<L>Vre iswinch and ure til&thorn;e. is ofte iwuned to swinden</L>
<L>ac &thorn;at we dot for godes luue. eft we it scullen a-finden</L>
<L>Ne scal non vuel ben vn-bout. ne non god vn-for-&yogh;olde</L>
<L N="60">vuel we do&eth; al to muchel. and god lasse &thorn;anne we scolde</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;e mest de&eth; nu to gode. and &thorn;e &thorn;e lest to la&eth;e
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="290"></L>
<L>ay&thorn;er to lutel and to muchel. scal &thorn;inchen eft hym ba&eth;e</L>
<L>&THORN;er me scal vre werkes we&yogh;en. bi-foren &thorn;en heuene kinge</L>
<L N="64">and &yogh;iuen us vre swinches lyen. after vre erninge</L>
<L>Eure ilc man mid &thorn;an &thorn;e he haued. mai biggen heueriche</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;e more haued and &thorn;e &thorn;e lasse. bo&thorn;e mai iliche</L>
<L>He alse mid his penie. se &thorn;e o&thorn;er mid his punde</L>
<L N="68">&thorn;at is &thorn;e wunder-likeste &yogh;are. &thorn;at eni man eure funde</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &thorn;e more ne mai don. bute mid his gode &thorn;anke</L>
<L>al se wel se &thorn;e haued. goldes feale manke</L>
<L>And god can more &thorn;anc. &eth;an &thorn;e him &yogh;iued lesse</L>
<L N="72">al his werkes and his weies. is milce and rit&yogh;ifnesse</L>
<L>Lutel loc is gode lef. &thorn;at comed of gode wille</L>
<L>and e&eth;-lete muchel &yogh;yue. &eth;enne &eth;e heorte is ille</L>
<L>Heuene and er&thorn;e he ouer-sih&eth;. his e&yogh;en bed so britte</L>
<L N="76">sunne. mone. dai. and fur. bud &thorn;ustre to-&yogh;enes his lithte</L>
<L>Nis him nout for-hole ni-hud. so muchel bet his mihte</L>
<L>nis it no so derne idon. ne a swa &thorn;ustre nihte</L>
<L>He wot wat deht and &thorn;enchet. alle quike wihte</L>
<L N="80">nis no louerd swilc se is crist. na king swilc vre drihte</L>
<L>Heuene and her&thorn;e and al &thorn;at is. be-loken in his honde</L>
<L>he ded al &thorn;at his willes is. a watere and a londe</L>
<L>He makede fisses inne &thorn;e see. and fu&yogh;eles inne &thorn;e lofte</L>
<L N="84">he wit and walt alle &thorn;ing. and he scop alle scefte</L>
<L>He is ord abuten orde. and ende a-buten ende</L>
<L>he one is eure on elche stede. wende war &thorn;u wende</L>
<L>He is buuen vs and bi-ne&thorn;en. bi-foren and bi-hinde</L>
<L N="88">&thorn;e &thorn;e godes wille &eth;e. ei&eth;er he mai him finde</L>
<L>Elche rune he i-hurd. and he wot alle dede</L>
<L>he &thorn;ur&eth;-sih&eth; elches mannes &thorn;anc. &thorn;at scal us to rede</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e breked godes hese. and gultet so ilome</L>
<L N="92">wet sulle hi segge o&thorn;er don. at &thorn;e muchele dome</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e luueden vnriht. and vuel lif ladde</L>
<L>wat scullen hi seggen o&thorn;er don. &thorn;ar engles bed of-dredde</L>
<L>Hwat sculle we beren bi-foren us. mid wan sculle we him i-quemen</L>
<L N="96">we &thorn;e neure god ne duden. &thorn;e heuenliche demen
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>&THORN;er sculle ben deofles swo fele. &thorn;e wulled us for-wreien</L>
<L>nabbet hi no&thorn;ing for-&yogh;yte. of al &thorn;at hi ere se&yogh;en</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at we mis-duden her. hit wullet cu&thorn;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="100">buten we habben it ibet. &thorn;e wile we her were</L>
<L>Al hi habbet an here i-write. &thorn;at we mis-duden here</L>
<L>&thorn;ei we it nusten ne i-seien. hi weren vre i-fere</L>
<L>Hwet scullen horlinges do. &thorn;e swikele &thorn;e for-sworene</L>
<L N="104">wi swo fele beod i-cleped. swa feuwe beod i-corene</L>
<L>Wi hwi were he bi-&yogh;ite. to wan were hi i-borene</L>
<L>&thorn;e sculle ben to de&thorn;e i-demd. and eure mo for-lorene</L>
<L>Elch man scal him sulne &thorn;ar. bi-clepiean and ec demen</L>
<L N="108">his a&yogh;e werc and his i&thorn;anc. to witnesce he scal temen</L>
<L>Ne mai hym na man al swa. wel demen ne al sa rithte</L>
<L>for nan ni-cnawed him swa wel. buten one dritte</L>
<L>Elc man wot him sulue best. his werc and his i-wille</L>
<L N="112">&thorn;e &thorn;e lest wot. seit ofte mest. and &thorn;e &thorn;e it wot is stille</L>
<L>Nis no witnesse al so muchel. so mannes howe heorte</L>
<L>hwa se segge &thorn;at he beo al. him self wat best his smerte</L>
<L>Elc man scal him suelf demen. to de&thorn;e o&thorn;er to liue</L>
<L N="116">&thorn;e witnesse of his owe werc. to o&thorn;er &eth;is him scal driue</L>
<L>Eal &thorn;at eure ilc man haued i-do. sut&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fut&thorn;e.</NOTE> he com to manne</L>
<L>swilc hit seie on boc i-writen. he scal it &thorn;enche &thorn;anne</L>
<L>Ac drithte ne demed nanne man. after his bi-ginninge</L>
<L N="120">ac his lif scal beo swulc. se bued his endinge</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if &thorn;e ende is euel, al it is uuel. and al god, &yogh;if god is ende</L>
<L>god &yogh;uue &thorn;at ure ende beo god. and wite &thorn;et he us lende</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;e nele do no god. ne neure god lif leden</L>
<L N="124">aer ded and dom come to his dure. he mai sore a-dreden</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne muwe &thorn;enne bidde ore. for it itit ilome</L>
<L>&thorn;i he is wis &thorn;e bit. and be-&yogh;it. and bet be-fore dome</L>
<L>&THORN;enne ded is ate dure. wel late he biddet ore</L>
<L N="128">wel late he leted vuel weorc. &thorn;e hit ne mai do na mare</L>
<L>Sunne let &thorn;e and &thorn;u naht hire &thorn;anne &thorn;us ne miht do no more</L>
<L>for-&thorn;i he is sot &thorn;e swa abit to habbe godes hore</L>
<L>&THORN;eh hwe&eth;er we it iluuet wel. for drihte sulf hit sede
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="292"></L>
<L N="132">a wulche time so eure &thorn;e man. of&thorn;inchet his misdede</L>
<L>O&thorn;er later o&thorn;er ra&thorn;er. milce he scal i-meten</L>
<L>ac &thorn;e &thorn;e nout naued ibet. wel muchel he scal beten</L>
<L>Mani man seid wo recke of pine. &thorn;e scal habben ende</L>
<L N="136">ne bidde ic no bet beo a-lused. a domesdai of bende</L>
<L>Lutel wat he hwat is pine. and lutel he it icwowe&eth;<NOTE PLACE="foot">So in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>wilc hete is &thorn;er soule wunet. hu biter wind &thorn;er blouwet</L>
<L>H&aelig;dde he ibeon &thorn;er anne dai. o&thorn;er twa bare tide</L>
<L N="140">nolde he for al midd&aelig;n eard. &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;er abide</L>
<L>&THORN;&aelig;t habbet ised &thorn;at comen &thorn;anne. &thorn;it wuste midiwisse</L>
<L>uuel is pine seoue &yogh;er. for seoue nihtes blisse</L>
<L>And ure blisse &thorn;e ende hafh.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So in MS.</NOTE> for endeliese pine</L>
<L N="144">betre is wori water to drinke. &thorn;enne atter i-menge mid wine</L>
<L>Swunes brede is swu&thorn;e swete. so is of wilde dere</L>
<L>ac al to duere he i-bu&yogh;ed. &thorn;at &yogh;iued &thorn;ere-fore his swere</L>
<L>Ful wombe mai liht-liche speken. of hunger and of fasten</L>
<L N="148">swa mai of pine &thorn;e naht not. hu hi scullen ilesten</L>
<L>H&aelig;dde he ifonded sume hwile. he wolde al seggen o&thorn;er</L>
<L>e&eth;-lete him were wif. and child. suster. and fader. and bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Al he wolde o&thorn;erluker don. and o&thorn;erluker &thorn;ench&aelig;</L>
<L N="152">&yogh;anne he bi-&thorn;ouhte on helle fur. &thorn;e nowiht ne mai aquenche</L>
<L>Eure he wolde inne wa her. and inne pine wunien</L>
<L>wid &thorn;an &thorn;e mihte helle pine. bi-fluen and bi-scunien</L>
<L>E&eth;-lete him were al woruldes wele. and al eordliche</L>
<L N="156">for to &thorn;e muchele murc&eth; cume. &thorn;at is heuenriche</L>
<L>Iwulle nu comen eft to &thorn;e dome. &thorn;at ic eow er of sede</L>
<L>on &thorn;at dai, and at &thorn;e dome. us helpe crist and rede</L>
<L>&THORN;&thorn;er we ma&yogh;en beon e&eth;e of-drad. and harde us adrede</L>
<L N="160">&thorn;er elc sceal i-seo bi-foren him. his word and ec his dede</L>
<L>Eal scal ben &thorn;anne cud. &thorn;at man lu&yogh;en her and stelen</L>
<L>al scal ben &thorn;er vnwrien. &thorn;at men wru&yogh;en her and helen</L>
<L>We scullen alre manne lif. icnawe &thorn;er al so vre owe</L>
<L N="164">&thorn;er sculle heueninges ben. &thorn;e hei&yogh;e and &thorn;e lou&yogh;e</L>
<L>Ne scal &thorn;ei noman scamien &thorn;er. ne &thorn;erf he him adrede</L>
<L>&yogh;if him here of-&thorn;inched his gult. and beted his misdede
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="293"></L>
<L>For heom ne scamet ne ne gramet. &thorn;e sculle beon iboruwene</L>
<L N="168">ac &thorn;e o&thorn;re habbet scame and grame. &thorn;at sculle beon forlorene</L>
<L>&THORN;e dom scal sone ben idon. ne last he nowit longe</L>
<L>ne scal him noman mene &thorn;er. of streng&thorn;e ne of wrange</L>
<L>&THORN;o scullen habbe hardne dom. &thorn;e here weren herde</L>
<L N="172">&thorn;a &thorn;e euele heolden wreche men. and vuele la&yogh;es rerde</L>
<L>Ac after &thorn;an &thorn;e he haued idon. he scal &thorn;er beon idemed</L>
<L>bli&thorn;e mai he &thorn;anne buen. &thorn;e god haued iquemed</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at isprunge be&eth;. of adam and of eue</L>
<L N="176">ealle he sculle &thorn;uder come. for so&thorn;e we it ileued</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e habbed wel idon. after heore mihte</L>
<L>to heuenriche he scullen. ford mid vre drihte</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e nabbe&eth; god idon. and &thorn;er-inne be&eth; ifunde</L>
<L N="180">he scullen falle swi&thorn;e ra&thorn;e. in to helle grunde</L>
<L>&THORN;&aelig;r-inne he scullen wunie. buten ore and ende</L>
<L>ne brec&eth; neuereuft crist helle dure. to lese hem of bende</L>
<L>Nis no sellic &thorn;ei heom beo wo. and hem beo vne&thorn;e</L>
<L N="184">nele neureit crist &thorn;olie de&eth;. for lesen heom of die&thorn;e</L>
<L>Enes drihte helle brac. his frend he ut broutte</L>
<L>him self he &thorn;olede die&eth; for hom. wel dore he us bouhte</L>
<L>Nolde it mouwe don for mey. ne suster for bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="188">nolde it sune don for fader. ne noman for o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Ure lauerd for his &thorn;reles. ipined was on rode</L>
<L>ure bendes he unbond. and bouht us mid his blode</L>
<L>We &yogh;ieued vne&thorn;e for his luue. a sticche of vre brede</L>
<L N="192">ne &thorn;enche we nout &thorn;at he scal deme. &thorn;o quike and to dede</L>
<L>Muchele luue he us cudde. wolde we it understondo</L>
<L>&thorn;at vre eldrene mis-duden. we habbet vuele an honde</L>
<L>Die&eth; com in &thorn;is middenerd. &thorn;urh &thorn;e ealde deofles onde</L>
<L N="196">and synne and sor&yogh;e and &yogh;e-swinch. a watere and ec alonde</L>
<L>Vres formes faderes gult. we abigget alle</L>
<L>al his of-sprung after hym. in herme is bi-falle</L>
<L>&THORN;urst. and hunger. chule. and hete. eche and al unel&thorn;e</L>
<L N="200">&thorn;urh died com in &thorn;is middenerd. and o&thorn;er vnisal&thorn;e</L>
<L>Niere no man elles died. ne sic. ne non vn-ysele</L>
<L>ac mihten libbe eure mo. a blisse and on hele
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>Lutel i&thorn;ench&eth; mani man. hu muchel wes &thorn;e synne</L>
<L N="204">for &thorn;an &thorn;olied alle died. &thorn;e comen of here cunne</L>
<L>Here synne and ec vre owen. sore us mai of-&thorn;inche</L>
<L>for in synne we libbet alle. in sorewen and in swinche</L>
<L>Sud&thorn;e god nam swa muchele wreche. for ane misdede</L>
<L N="208">we &thorn;at so muchel and swa oft mis-do&eth;. mu&yogh;en vs sore adrede</L>
<L>Adam and his of-spring. for one bare sunne</L>
<L>was fele hundred wintre in helle. in pine and in vnwunne</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;e leded here lif mid vnriht and mid wronge</L>
<L N="212">bute it godes milce do sculle beo &thorn;er wel longe</L>
<L>Godes wisdom is wel muchel. and al swa is his mihte</L>
<L>and nis his milce nawiht lasse. ac bi &eth;es ilke wihte</L>
<L>More he one mai for-&yogh;iuen. &thorn;enne alfolc gulte cunne</L>
<L N="216">Deofel suelf mihte habbe milce. &yogh;if he it bidde gunne</L>
<L>&THORN;e &eth;e godes milce sech&eth;. iwis he mai is finde</L>
<L>ac helle king is oreles. wi&eth; &thorn;a &thorn;e he mai binde</L>
<L>&THORN;e &eth;e de&eth; his wille mest. he haue&eth; wurst mede</L>
<L N="220">his bea&eth; scal beo wallinde pich. his bed berninde glede</L>
<L>Wurs he de&eth; his gode wines. &thorn;ene his fulle feonde</L>
<L>god sculde alle godes frend a wihd scuche freonde</L>
<L>Neure on helle ic ne com ne comen ic &thorn;er ne reche</L>
<L N="224">&eth;eh ich elches wurldes wele. &thorn;er-inne mihte fecche</L>
<L>&THORN;eh ic wulle seggen eow. &thorn;at wise men us sede</L>
<L>and aboke it is i-write. &thorn;er me mai it rede</L>
<L>Ic it wulle segge heom &thorn;e hem self it nusten</L>
<L N="228">and warnen heom wit heore hearme. &yogh;if hi me wulled lusten</L>
<L>Vnder-stondet nu to me. &aelig;idi men and earme</L>
<L>Ic wulle telle of helle pine. and warnie ow wi&eth; herme</L>
<L>On helle is vnger and &thorn;erst. vuele tuo ifere</L>
<L N="232">&thorn;os pine &thorn;olied &thorn;o &thorn;e were. mete ni&thorn;inges here</L>
<L>&THORN;or is woninge and wop. after eche strete</L>
<L>hi fared fram hete to &thorn;e chele. fram chele to &thorn;e hete</L>
<L>&THORN;anne hi beod in &thorn;e hete. &thorn;e chele &eth;inchet blisse</L>
<L N="236">&thorn;enne hi come&eth; eft to chele. of hete hi habbed misse</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er hem de&eth; wa inou. nabbet hi none lisse</L>
<L>nuten hi we&thorn;er heom ded wurst. mid neure non iwisse
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>Hi walked eure and sechet reste. ac hi ne mu&yogh;en imeten</L>
<L N="240">for-&thorn;i hi nolden &thorn;o wile hi mithten here sunne beten</L>
<L>Hi seched reste &thorn;er non nis. ac &thorn;i ne muwen ifinde</L>
<L>ac walked weri up and dun. al se water de&eth; mid winde</L>
<L>&THORN;is beod &thorn;o &thorn;e weren her. on &thorn;onke vn-stedefaste</L>
<L N="244">and &thorn;o god bi-heten auht. and nolden it ilaste</L>
<L>&THORN;o &eth;e god weorc bi-gunne. and ful-enden hit nolden</L>
<L>&thorn;e weren her and nu&thorn;e &thorn;er. and nusten wet he wolden</L>
<L>&THORN;ere is pich &thorn;at eure weal&eth;. &thorn;at sculle ba&thorn;ien inne</L>
<L N="248">&thorn;o &thorn;e ladde vuel lif. in feoh end in iginne</L>
<L>&THORN;er is fur &thorn;at eure barn&eth;. ne mai hit nawiht quenche</L>
<L>her-inne beod &thorn;e wes to lef. wrecche men to swenche</L>
<L>&THORN;er is fur &thorn;at is vndredfelde hatere &thorn;anne beo vre</L>
<L N="252">ne mai it quenchen salt water. nauene strien ne sture</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e were swikele men. and fulle of vuele wrenche</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e ne mihte euel don. and lef was it to &thorn;enche</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e luueden reuing and stale. hordom. and drunke</L>
<L N="256">and &thorn;e on &thorn;es deofles weorkes bli&thorn;eliche swunke</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e were so lease. &thorn;at me hi ne mihte ileuen</L>
<L>med &yogh;eorne domes men. and wrancwise reuen</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;re mannes wif wes lef. his awene e&eth;-lete</L>
<L N="260">and &thorn;o &thorn;e sunegede muchel. on drunke and on ete</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrecchen bi-nemen hure ehte. and leiden huere on horde</L>
<L>&thorn;e lutel leten of godes bode. and of godes worde</L>
<L>And of his owen nolde &yogh;iuen. &thorn;er he sei &thorn;e nede</L>
<L N="264">ne nolde i-huren godes sonde. &thorn;er he sette his beode</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e weren o&thorn;eres mannes &thorn;inc. leure &thorn;anne it scolde</L>
<L>and weren al to gredi. of suelfer and of golde</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;e vntreunesse deden. &yogh;am hi ahte ben holde</L>
<L N="268">and leten &thorn;at hi scolde don. and duden &thorn;et hi wolde</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e &yogh;ysceres weren of &thorn;is woruldes ehte</L>
<L>and dude &thorn;at &thorn;e lo&thorn;e gost. hem tihte and ec tauhte</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;o &eth;en eni wise. deoflen her iquemde</L>
<L N="272">&thorn;o beo&eth; nu mid him an helle for-don and for-dempde<NOTE PLACE="foot">For remainder see Text, pp. 175-183.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
